Ian Darwin wrote:

&gt; I&#39;m trying to write a test runner for a new &quot;subframework&quot; that will 
&gt; read an arbitrary
&gt; number of tests from a &quot;little language&quot; scripting file, and I&#39;m 
&gt; trying to write this as a Test class
&gt; (my framework will be released as open source when it is working).
&gt;
&gt; I started with the assumption that if the framework calls a Test&#39;s 
&gt; countTestCases
&gt; it will next call its run() method once and let it run all the tests, 
&gt; and that it expects the
&gt; test to call results.startTest(this) and endTest(this).  So this is a 
&gt; gloss of my test: is this
&gt; at all the right approach?


Due to the overwhelming silence on this issue, I came up with a 
different way that seems to work.



  ----------

package regress;

import junit.framework.AssertionFailedError;
import junit.framework.Test;
import junit.framework.TestResult;
import junit.framework.TestSuite;

/** The suite() method way of running multiple tests within a single source file.
 * @author ian darwin
 */
public class MyTest2  {
	static int i = 0; 

	/** This class is a short-term stand-in for my actual tests, which will have
	 * been read from a file...
	 * @author ian
	 */
	static class MyUnitBaseTest implements Test {
		int counter;
		MyUnitBaseTest() {
			counter = i++;
		}
		public int countTestCases() {
			return 1;
		}

		public void run(TestResult result) {
			result.startTest(this);
			try {
				Thread.sleep(250);
			} catch (InterruptedException e) {
				// canthappen
			}
			// Just throw some Failures and Errors in to see if the display works correctly.
			if (counter == 6) {
				result.addFailure(this, new AssertionFailedError(&quot;boo hoo&quot;));
			} else if (counter == 8) {
				result.addError(this, new RuntimeException(&quot;wah&quot;));
			}
			result.endTest(this);
		}	
		public String toString() {
			return &quot;MyInnerTest: &quot; + counter;
		}
	}

	public static Test suite() {
		TestSuite tests = new TestSuite(&quot;Test for my package&quot;);
		// This for loop will be replaced by code that reads the tests from the script file
		// and makes Test instances out of them. TestCase stores its results in a Vector,
		// whose elements() method returns an Enumeration that does run the tests in the correct order
		// (unlike when you use the JUnit &quot;find all test methods beginning with test&quot; approach,
		// in which case the order is undocumented, presumably based on Class.getMethods()).
		for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++)
			tests.addTest(new MyUnitBaseTest());
		return tests;
	}
}


